You can do it. You can consider using the BeanParam annotation, then your service definition will be:

    MyReturnResponse getData(@BeanParam MyRequestClass apiRequest);

then you need to annotate each parameter on the Java Bean:

    public class MyRequestClass {
        @QueryParam(&quot;name&quot;) 
        @NotNull(message = &quot;application name is required&quot;)
        public String applicationName;

        @QueryParam
        @NotNull(message = &quot;code type is required&quot;)
        public String codeType;

        @QueryParam
        @NotNull(message = &quot;request date is required&quot;)
        public String requestDate;
    }

with this configuration you are able to call the service with a similar request:

    /apiData?name=ApplicationName&amp;codeType=MyType&amp;requestDate=2021-10-21

With BeanParam you are telling the framework that the configuration will be placed on the JavaBean, inside the bean you can define any amount of parameters, not only query parameters, you can include Header, Path and Form parameters if you need (with the appropriate method POST, PUT, etc.)

